description: From Middle French architecte, from Latin architectus, from Ancient Greek ἀρχιτέκτων (arkhitéktōn, “master builder”), from ἀρχι- (arkhi-, “chief”) + τέκτων (téktōn, “builder”).

entries.meaning: A professional who designs buildings or other structures, or who prepares plans and superintends construction.
examples: Plato made the causes of things to be matter, ideas, and an efficient architect.

entries.meaning: A person who plans, devises or contrives the achievement of a desired result.
examples: Peisistratus was the first architect of the Iliad and the Odyssey.

entries.meaning: (Philippines) An honorific given to architects. Usually capitalized or abbreviated as Arch./Ar. before the person's name.

verbs.description: architect (third-person singular simple present architects, present participle architecting, simple past and past participle architected)

examples: He architected the military coup against the government.
